<ns399:section xmlns:ns399="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2ee.ejb.client.rmiClients.overview">

  <ns400:title xmlns:ns400="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">RMI clients</ns400:title>
  <ns401:para xmlns:ns401="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    RMI clients use the RMI/IIOP protocol to access enterprise beans.
    They are typically remote clients, though local clients and even 
    local enterprise beans may behave like remote clients by requesting
    bean services over RMI.
  </ns401:para>
  <ns402:para xmlns:ns402="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    RMI clients obtain bean references from a naming service. It is
    preferable that clients decouple from any concrete realization
    of a naming service by using the JNDI, the <ns403:emphasis xmlns:ns403="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java
    Naming and Directory Interface</ns403:emphasis>.
  </ns402:para>
  <ns404:para xmlns:ns404="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    RMI clients are typically either
    <ns405:itemizedlist xmlns:ns405="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns406:listitem xmlns:ns406="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns407:para xmlns:ns407="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">applications,</ns407:para></ns406:listitem>
      <ns408:listitem xmlns:ns408="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns409:para xmlns:ns409="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">applets, or</ns409:para></ns408:listitem>
      <ns410:listitem xmlns:ns410="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns411:para xmlns:ns411="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        servlets residing in servlet containers which do not run
        within the same virtual machine as the application server.
      </ns411:para></ns410:listitem>
    </ns405:itemizedlist>
  </ns404:para>
</ns399:section>